ing the winter and more or less dries up in summer, such as Winterburn in Gargrave (Yorkshire), Winterbourne (Berkshire, Gloucestershire), Winterbourne Bassett (Wiltshire), or one of thirteen parishes named Winterborne in Dorset, including Winterborne Abbas, Winterborne Monkton, and Winterborne Zelstone. In most cases, the form <i>Winterburn</i> can be associated with Winterburn in Gargrave (Yorkshire), though no such association can be made between other surname forms and corresponding placenames."]}]},{"name":"Alice","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Adelaide  , representing an Old French spelling of a reduced form of Germanic <i>Adalheidis</i>. <i>Alice</i> and <i>Adelaide</i> were already regarded as distinct names in English during the medieval period. <i>Alice</i> enjoyed a surge of popularity in the 19th century and periods of favour ever since. It was the name of the central character of  Lewis Carroll's  Alice's Adventures in Wonderland (  1865 ) and Through the Looking Glass (  1872 ), who was based on his child friend  Alice Liddell , daughter of the Dean of Christ Church, Oxford."],"variants":[{"name":"Alys","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Alice ."]},{"name":"Alis","meanings":["equivalent of <b>Alice</b> ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Alice de Winterbourne was born about 1355, her father, Sir John De Winterbourne, was 53 and her mother, Lady. John de Winterbourne, was 57. She had at least 2 sons with Sir Walter Herring. She died in Dorset, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"about 1355–":"umbes 1355–Surnud","1355–Female":"1355–Surnud","1350–Male":"1350–Surnud","1372–1456":"1372–1456","1374–Male":"1374–Surnud","1304–Male":"1304–Surnud","1300–Female":"1300–Surnud","1304":"1304","1456":"1456","1300":"1300","1355":"1355","Abt 1320":"umbes 1320","1374":"1374","1372":"1372","1350":"1350","about 1355":"umbes 1355","about 1372":"umbes 1372","England":"